description.plain: Destiny Nicole Frasqueri (born June 14, 1992) is an Afro-Puerto Rican independent alternative hip hop and alternative R&B recording artist and songwriter based in New York City. Formerly known by her stage names “Wavy Spice” or “Destiny”, she currently performs under the name Princess Nokia, which she describes as her artistic alter ego.

songs.title: Tomboy

description.plain:
“Tomboy,” is the second track of Princess Nokia’s 2017 album 1992 Deluxe. The song is about Princess Nokia being proud of her body and owning her sexuality. In an interview with Mass appeal Princess Nokia talked about Tomboy and said,

By falling in love with all your flaws. I’ve done fallen in love with all of mine. I see my existence as a big fuck you to conventionality. Sure I have little titties and a phat belly, but that doesn’t make me less of a goddess, less of an aphrodisiac.

songs.title: Brujas

description.plain: “Bruja” is the word meaning “witch” in Spanish. Princess Nokia gives a shoutout to her Puerto Rican and Yoruban ancestry, saying her grandmas were brujas, strong women who demanded respect and mystified others. In this song the stereotype of the voodoo witch doctor is addressed, saying that African witchcraft is so much more than what European people have portrayed it as.

songs.full_title: Saggy Denim by Princess Nokia (Ft. Wiki)
songs.title: Saggy Denim

description.plain:
Fashion and Hip-Hop have always had a symbiotic relationship, and Saggy Denim is a celebration of not only Princess Nokia’s romantic life and her ethnicity, but the fashion culture of the world she grew up in: ‘90s New York. With the likes of Biggie Smalls, Jay-Z, the Wu-Tang Clan repping everything from baggy jeans and windbreakers to lavish silk scarves and maroon suits (See Ol’ Dirty Bastard at the 2000 Grammy Awards), style was a part of self-expression in the hip-hop world.

Certain brands have a particular stake in the culture: Tommy Hilfiger, Ralph Lauren, Calvin Klein, to cite those named in this track. The trail blazed by the likes of the Wu has been taken up by current New York rappers like the self-proclaimed ‘fashion killa’ A$AP Rocky, the MC Wiki who modeled for Supreme in 2016, and of course Princess Nokia herself. From subverting heteronormative fashion with Biggie-esque sweatshirts and chains in the music video for “Tomboy” to roaming the streets in an oversized New York Nicks windbreaker in her video for “Green Line” to fronting iconic brands (not just clothes – Phillies cigars, for example, are referenced on track 1 of Nas’s Illmatic, the holy grail of ‘90’s NYC culture) Princess Nokia embodies the history of New York rap’s multifaceted scene.

songs.full_title: ABCs of New York by Princess Nokia
songs.title: ABCs of New York

description.plain: In “Abcs of New York,”  Princess Nokia expresses her love for New York where she lived in East Harlem and the lower side of New York City. She talks about all of the many people in the big city without using a hook or chorus. Princess Nokia also told Rob Markman on For the Record that this song was inspired by Papoose’s “Alphabetical Slaughter.”

songs.title: Green Line

description.plain: The ‘Green Line’ is New York’s 6 Lexington Avenue/Pelham Local rapid transit train that runs from Pelham Bay Park in the Bronx to Brooklyn Bridge/City Hall in Lower Manhattan. By virtue of its connecting the Bronx, Harlem and the Upper and Lower East sides, it is literally at the center of modern New York’s history and culture. Princess Nokia uses the song title and the epithet ‘Green Line Chick’ as a synecdoche to explore the sprawling, ever-changing areas and flavors of New York, from Afro-Latinx to Italian American communities.
